column5: Instructions for a computer's processor to perform specific operations e.g. system software such as Windows and iOS, application software such as internet browsers and apps.
A lot of applications use large complicated databases for storing information. The software in this category has been designed to make building and managing these databases fast and easy.

The operating system is the program that gets started first when you switch on your computer or server. All other applications depend on it for correct operation. Some examples of popular operating systems are Microsoft Windows, Mac OS and Linux.
column6: El sistema operativo es el programa que se inicia primero al encender el ordenador o servidor. Todas las demás aplicaciones dependan del sistema operativo para su correcto funcionamiento. Algunos ejemplos de sistemas operativos más populares son Microsoft Windows, Mac OS y Linux.

column5: Set of computer programs used for work/business including a word processor, spreadsheet and presentation program. An example of an office suite is Microsoft Office.
Computer programs that can be used for financial analysis.
Computer programs that can be used for accounting purposes.
Computer programs that allow information to be presented in various formats, such as text, audio and video.
Computer programs that can understand the spoken words of the user. The software can do various things with the speech, such as convert it into text or use it to perform an internet search.
Optical character reader (OCR) software.
Computer programs where a slide show or other presentation can be created and presented e.g. PowerPoint
Computer programs where the layout, contents and typography of the document can be changed by the user so a professional-looking document can be present or published.
Computer programs which allow a user to compose, edit, format and print written material such a letter or report. A common example of a word processor is Microsoft Word.
Computer programs which allow a user to create, modify and analyse a design.
Computer programs which allow a user to edit static or moving images e.g. Adobe Photoshop.
Computer programs which alow a user to plan, organize and manage resources.
Computer programs which allow a user to organize and analyse data in a table, and create graphs and graphics. A common example is Microsoft Excel.
Computer programs which allow users to create and print labels for products etc.
Computer programs that allow audio content (e.g. music, voice recordings) to be edited.
Development software or a programming tool is a program or application that software developers use to create, debug, or maintain other programs and applications.
Computer programs that help your computer to perform better e.g. anti-virus software, disk repair software, file management software.
Computer programs which translate from one language to another.
Computer programs which allow individual files, programs or systems to be protected using passwords, face recognition etc.
Computer programs which allow a user to create bar codes for products.
Computer programs which store a "backup" (another copy) of your data in case the software/computer closes or crashes unexpectedly.
Computer programs which make it easy to manage your computer, and help you work faster and more efficiently.
Computer programs which protect computer systems, files and software from computer viruses.
Computer programs which allow users to manage printing devices.
Computer programs which allow a user to view and control software and hardware on an individual device or across a network.
Software for managing all your storage media and stored data.
Computer programs which allow a user to set up, control and manage a network or networks between computers, printers and other devices.
Computer programs which display video terminals through some another type of program, such as text.
Computer programs which allow a user to control a modem and ensure it is functioning correctly.
Computer programs which controls the switch and router, which link computers in a network.
Computer program which controls a communications server, which is a carrier-grade computing system to control network infrastructure
Static or moving images which appear on your computer screen after a certain amount of inactivity, the time of which can be set by the user.
Electronic games which involves a human interacting with a user interface, generating visual feedback on a video device such as a laptop, games console or handheld device.
Computer programs which allow videos to be displayed on a device.
Computer program which allows you to access a data system from a remote location, for example through a VPN (virtual private network).
Computer games, videos and other media that is suitable for all ages.
Computer programs which aim to teach the user something e.g. software aimed at learning a language.
A hardware component of a computer such as a hard disk or memory.
Portable computer devices and phones, and their accessories such as cables and stands

A mobile phone, also known as a cellphone, mobile, or handphone, is an electronic telecommunications device with the same basic capability as a conventional fixed line telephone, but which is also entirely portable and is not required to be connected with a wire to the telephone network. With most modern cellphones you can do a lot more than just making phonecalls: with most models you can send an SMS or e-mail, surf the internet, play games, save phone numbers so you'll never have to write down or memorize them again and much, much more.
Call your friends, business partners or customers with one of these great telephones!
Equipment that allows you to interconnect circuits of telephones to establish telephone calls between different users.
Equipment that allows you to connect two or more different locations via telephone lines
Device or stand where you can rest your mobile or fixed telephone.
System to control calls through to a company or organisation, such as a switchboard.

A headset is just a combination of a headphone (with one or two ear plugs) and a microphone. Headsets with one ear plug are used mostly for calling hands-free, while the ones featuring a full headphone are better suited for communicating with your teammates in games.
column6: Los auriculares o audifonos son una combinación de auricular de teléfono (con uno o dos tapones) y un micrófono. Auriculares con un solo tapón se usan generalmetne para las llamadas de manos libres, mientras que aquellos completos se utilizan para comunicaciones de equipo en algún juego.

column5: A machine which records a voice message when someone rings a phone and there is no answer or the line is engaged.
Device which creates a wireless network by sending out radio waves across a certain range.
Equipment that permits conferences to take place in different locations by connecting participants through audio (telephone) and video devices.

A platform into which you can install a portable computer. The docking station typically contains slots for expansion cards, bays for storage devices, and I/O connectors for peripheral devices, such as printers and monitors. Once inserted in a docking station, the portable computer essentially becomes a desktop model computer. Most importantly, the same data is accessible in both modes because it resides on the portable computer's drives. The idea behind docking stations is to let you simultaneously enjoy the expansion possibilities of desktop model computers with the portability of notebook computers. In addition, the docking station enables you to use a full-size keyboard and monitor when you're not traveling.

Personal Computers, PCs for short, are computers for personal usage. They always have the following components:

- A processor (CPU), this is the heart of your computer, where the data processing is done.

- Memory (RAM), this is very fast memory in which temporary data is stored before being processed by the processor.

- Motherboard, this is the component that connects all the different parts of your computer. Often it has some integrated components like a sound card, enabling your computer to play sound, or a network card, to connect your computer to the network.

- Video board, this is the part of your computer that is responsible for the graphics processing. Micro ATX motherboards often have an integrated video board. Those integrated video boards are generally not very well suited for playing games, but good enough for watching movies.

- Hard disk, this is the permanent memory of your computer where your data is stored.

- An optional DVD/CD player/recorder for reading/writing DVDs/CDs.
Mobile computer which uses RFID (Radio Frequency Identification) e.g. scanning devices in shops and restaurants

Extra powerful, extra reliable computers that have been specially designed for server applications. For example serving a website, a large database or shared storage space to a lot of users. Servers are often not very quiet and deliver hardly any graphical performance, which makes them not suitable for use as personal computer. If you need a lot of servers, choose a rack mountable model. Those models need less space and your server room will remain tidy.
Point of sale terminals
Device which improves the quality of power that is delivered to electric load equipment.
Device which is programmed to carry out a set of arithmetic or logical operations e.g. desktop computers, smartphones

A notebook, also known as laptop, is a portable computer. When you are looking for the right notebook, it is important to know where you are going to work with it. Do you want to use it on the road? Choose a model with a special energy-saving 'mobile' processor, a good battery and a reasonably small display. This will allow you to work longer with the same battery and saves you the trouble of carrying around a large display that consumes a lot of precious battery power. Or will you be using you notebook mainly in places where you will have access to a power outlet? Then choose a desktop processor (more processing power for less money) and an ordinary battery. This will save you a lot of money, which you could then spend on a bigger screen.  You'll work faster because you can view more information at once and it's great for multimedia!

The graphics card, also known as the video card, is the complete graphical subsystem of the PC. It is responsible for the quality and speed of video processing. For users that wish to play games or work with multimedia applications, it is especially important to have a video board with a high performance graphics processor and enough memory.
An explansion board you insert into your computer so the computer can be connected to a network

A sound card or audio board allows computers to play and record sound. If you have a 5.1 or 7.1 audio board, you can connect your computer to your home cinema set for the real cinema experience, with full surround sound, whilst playing games or viewing DVDs.
A point of interaction between computer hardware or software and peripheral devices such as computer monitor or a keyboard

The motherboard or mainboard is the component that connects all the different parts of your computer. Often it has some integrated components like a sound card, enabling your computer to play sound, or a network card, to connect your computer to the network. The standard form factor (size) for motherboards is ATX, you need at least a midi-tower to fit one of those in. Micro-ATX motherboards are often more complete and have more onboard devices, like a video board and fit in smaller cases, but are generally less expandable.
Devices that convert an analog video signal (such as that produced by a DVD or video player) into a digital signal which can then be shown on a computer.
Musical instrument digital interface (MIDI) interfaces or adapters.
column6: Musical instrument digital interface (MIDI) interfaces or adapters

column5: Devices that feed data into a computer e.g. keyboard, joystick
Package of hardware and software that adds multimedia capabilities to a computer e.g. DVD player, sound card.
Device which does the reverse of an encoder, undoing the code so that the original information can be retrieved.

A NIC or Network Interface Card is a circuit board or chip which allows the computer to communicate to other computers on a network. When connected to the network, computers can share websites, files, printers and other resources. The most popular networking standard at the moment is Ethernet, which one can recognize by the rectangular connectors with eight wires in them. Wireless network with the 802.11b and the faster 802.11g standard is also increasingly popular, both at home and in the office, though it is not yet as fast as wired (ethernet) network. A public place where you can use wireless internet is called a "hot spot".

A mouse pad is very useful when you still have a mouse with a ball in it. It provides better grip for the ball on the surface, so you can work more conveniently with your mouse. For the newer optical and laser mice it is important to have an entirely flat surface to work on. Not all mouse pads provide this, so have a close look at the surface of the pad before buying it if you intend to use it with the latter kind.
Device able to store and retrieve data.
Small pen-shaped instrument used to input commands onto a computer screen, mobile device or graphics tablet.
Wireless computer input device which allows users to point to items on a screen on write and draw on screen.
With a scanner you can make all your documents, pictures and photos digital.
Device which is similar to a TV remote control and is used to wirelessly control a presentation on a computer such as on Powerpoint .
Input device mainly used in laptops instead of a mouse. By moving your finger over the touchpad you move the cursor.

In this category you will find accessories for playing games, both for your computer and your games console. Take control of the game and leave your opponents far behind. With these accessories your games will become more real than life!

On a graphic tablet you can write and make drawings with special pen. The information your graphic tablet receives is transferred to your computer and can be displayed as a drawing on your screen. With the appropriate software, it is even possible to write in handwriting on your graphic tablet instead of typing.

The mouse is the second most important way of communicating with a computer. Please be careful to choose the right type of connection when buying a mouse, there are three different types:

- USB is the most modern. You can recognize it by the rectangular connector.

- PS/2 connectors are round. This type of connection is fairly commonly used in PCs.

- Bluetooth is another modern (wireless) connection method.

The keyboard is the main input peripheral used by all computers. The keyboard allows for user input and interaction with the computer. Much like many typewriters the keyboard has all the letters of the alphabet, numbers 0 - 9 and additional special operational keys, e.g. for adjusting the volume or going to your inbox directly. There are three different connection types:

- USB is the most modern. You can recognize it by the rectangular connector.

- PS/2 connectors are round. This type of connection is fairly commonly used by PC's.

- Bluetooth is another modern (wireless) connection method.

These monitors were until recently the standard in computer monitors. Nowadays most people use TFT/LCD displays because they are less bulky and use less energy. There are however still some advantages in buying a CRT monitor, especially so if you're looking for a 19" or bigger model. You won't be able to lift them easily, but they are often much more affordable and capable of displaying higher resolutions. Make sure you buy a model that has a refresh rate of at least 70 Hz at the desired viewing resolution, or you will get tired eyes after prolonged usage.

TFT/LCD displays are perfectly flat, a lot thinner and lighter than conventional CRT displays and do not flicker, all this because of the new technology they use for producing images. Do you want to free up space on your desk, or do you want to be able to move your monitor without breaking your back? Then this is the perfect display for you!
Monitors, common on smartphones and tablets, which respond to touch.
Racks that can hold a number of tape drives.

Storage device which contains one or more tape drive, a number of slots to hold tape cartridges, a barcode reader to identify tape cartridges and an automated method for loading tapes. A tape library with one drive is known as an auto loader.

Hard disk drives are today's fastest permanent storage media and have a large capacity. For this two reasons they are the most used storage medium in computers and servers. When buying a new hard disk, there are three important things to consider:

- The connection of the disk to the computer or other device you will be using it with has a big influence on the speed with which data can be read from/written to the disk. Make sure the connection of the disk you buy is compatible with your computer!

- The rotational speed is also important for the speed with which data can be read from/written to the disk and determines the time it takes to find a file on the disk.

- Last but not least, the storage capacity of the disk, i.e. the amount of data that can be stored on the disk.

With these drives you can read and record DVDs and/or CDs in all kinds of formats. Please note the difference between DVD+R and DVD-R when buying a DVD burner, often drives can write only to one of those two media types, sometimes to both. When you buy a drive that only supports one type, you will always have to be careful to choose the right writable DVD discs in the shop. Newer DVD drives also support writing to Dual Layer DVDs. This kind of discs have a storage capacity of 8.5 GB instead of the usual 4.7 GB. DVD (re)writers generally can read and write CDs also, but only some CD (re)writers can read DVDs.
column6: Devices for reading and recording information from CD or DVD disks.

column5: Tape drives are a cost-effective solution for backing up all your important data when high speed is not required.
Robotic data storage device that can automatically load and unload optical discs such as DVDs and CDs. Often have up to 2000 slots for discs.
Group of two or more hard discs used to increase performance and enables fault tolerance.

Floppy disks, also known as floppies, are a fairly old-fashioned data storage medium. The advantage of using floppies is that most computers have a floppy drive. However, storage capacity is very limited with only 1.4 MB for the most commonly used 3.5" floppies, and floppy disks can be easily damaged by dust in the drive.
A long narrow slot in a computer into which an expansion card can be inserted.
Metal shell which contains the components of a network.
A computer case, also known as a chassis, is an empty metal shell used to protect computer components.
Components which fit inside the chassis, which is the metal shell used to protect computer parts. Examples of such components are motherboards and CPUs.

Laser printers are devices that print high quality text or illustrations fast. They do so by very accurately applying toner (a kind of ink powder) to the paper and then heating the paper so the toner will melt and stick to the paper.
Inkjet printers are the most suitable printers for home and small office use. They are generally not as fast as laser printers, but make prints of very high quality and are quite affordable.
Printer which prints a page-wide line of dots and builds up a line of text by printing a line of dots.
These printers have been designed for printing on media larger than A4. Perfect for printing impressive posters!
Create your own, professional looking labels fast and conveniently with one of these label printers!

A dot matrix printer or impact matrix printer is a type of printer with a print head that prints by impact, striking an ink-soaked cloth ribbon against the paper, much like a typewriter. Unlike a typewriter, letters are drawn out of a dot matrix, consisting of needles, and thus varied fonts and arbitrary graphics can be produced. Because the printing is done by applying mechanical pressure, these printers can create carbon copies.
A line printer that uses a metal band, or loop, of type characters as its printing mechanism. It can print over 2000 lines per minute.
Ability to print and scan documents using a device such as an all-in-one printer and scanner.

Device which can access the ISDN. The ISDN is a  telephone network which is able to transmit digital data. ISDNs can be accessed through a Basic Rate Interface (BRI) or a Primary Rate Interface (PRI).
Device which converts digital data from computers into electric signals which can be transmitted over a telephone line, and convert electric signals which it receives into digital data for computers.

A hub that connects a group of computers to a "token ring" local area network (LAN). A "token ring" is a LAN in which all computers are connected in a ring or star topology, and a bit- or token-passing scheme is used in order to prevent the collision of data between two computers that want to send messages at the same time.
Piece of a telecommunications circuit that transforms digital data between telephone company lines and local equipment.
Software which restricts or controls the media content (e.g on the internet) that a user can access.

With a router you can connect networks. Most people will use a router to connect their local (wireless) home or office network (LAN) with the Internet. The router makes sure that all computers on the local network can connect with one another, with shared resources and with the Internet and can be configured to forward requests for connections from computers on the internet to the appropriate local computer. In order to connect your local network to the internet via an ADSL or cable, you also need an (Ethernet) ADSL or cable modem if it is not built-in in the router, which is most likely to be the case.
column6: Un router, en español ruteador o encaminador es un dispositivo de hardware para interconexión de redes de ordenadores. Un router es un dispositivo que permite asegurar el enrutamiento de paquetes entre redes o determinar la ruta que debe tomar el paquete de datos.

column5: A telecommunications network which allows computers and other electronic devices to exchange data. Common examples are local area networks (LANs) and virtual private networks (VPNs).

An interface is a point of interaction with software, hardware or peripheral devices such as a computer monitor or keyboard. An interface hub is where there are several interfaces together in one place.
A type of metal shelf which contains servers.
Electronic device for reading printed barcodes.
Switch which allows one printer to be shared by more than one computer.

A keyboard, video, mouse (KVM) switch allows you to connect multiple computers to one keyboard, mouse, and display. You can switch between the different computers by a simple keystroke, without (un)plugging a single wire.
Computer interface components which allow communication between computers and external devices.
Tape, disc or other device which can store data.

A switch is a device with which it is possible to connect computers into a (local area) network, provided your computers all have an appropriate networking device installed. Switches can be daisy chained to form larger networks and come in managed and unmanaged variaties. The unmanaged versions generally cannot filter data and will forward any data that is fed into them, so they are better suited for small networks. Switches are easy to set up (just plug in the network cables) and allow you to share printers, storage space and other network resources with your entire home or office network.
Device which can be used to connect a modem to a telephone line.

With a bridge you can connect different types of networks, e.g. a wireless network and an Ethernet network. A repeater expands the reach of your wireless network, which comes in handy if you have a bad or slow connection in some remote corners of your home or office.

A multifunctional is really an all-in-one device; it is both a scanner and a printer, and often even has a fax function. So effectively it's a copier, but one that has the scanning and printing functions available separately. All this is a great advantage when you have limited office space. Moreover, you will be able to work faster and more efficiently by using the device's convenient special functions.
Organize all your documents by perforating them and storing them in ring binders. Give your reports a professional look, have them bound. With these devices you can do all that and more!
Use a paper cutter to cut all your documents in the right format. A paper cutter is fast, efficient and the results are much better than those achieved with scissors.

Have your printer print on both sides of the paper automatically with one of these duplex units. Safv up to 50% on paper and work more efficiently when printing booklets. Save both money and the environment!
Enlarge the input capacity of your printer with an extra tray, so you can print longer with less maintenance.
Small portable device used to perform arithmetic.

Diskettes, also known as floppy disks or floppies for short, are a fairly old fashioned data storage medium. The big advantage of using floppy disks is that a lot of computers have a diskette drive, but a rather large disadvantage is that you can only store 1.4 MB on an ordinary 3.5" floppy.

Recordable CDs (CD-R) on which you can store your data in different formats, depending on the features of your CD/DVD Writer. If you want to record CDs at the maximum speed of your CD/DVD Writer, please make sure you pick CDs that support this speed. ReWritable CDs (CD-RW) are a special type of CD, which you can overwrite time and time again (up to some limited number). Ordinary CDs can only be used once.
Empty data tapes for making back ups or storing huge amounts of data.

column3: high density removable media blank disks
column4: discos en blanco de alta densidad
column5: Blank disks that can store a large amount of data and can be removed from the device e.g CDs, DVDs.
These goods will help you in organising your storage media collection, increasing its life time.\n\nCD/DVD cases keep your CDs/DVDs clean and free of scratches and make them easy to organise.
An office is a room, floor or building where business is conducted.
Copy all your documents fast and easy with one of these copiers!

With a facsimile (fax) it is possible to send documents to and receive from other facsimiles; all you need is your existing phone line. Often facsimiles also have a copy (scan & print) function, although the quality of the copies is not always that great for most machines.
Films such as plastic used to cover other materials such as paper.
Device which imprints something on another surface.
Supplies needed for printing such as ink cartridges and toners.
Devices in laser printers or photocopiers which melts the toner onto the paper.
Toner cartridges for your laser printer or copier.
Component in printers used to transfer colour onto paper.
Cloths for cleaning the fuser in a laser printer or photocopier.

A fuser is a pair of heated rollers in a laser printer/photocopier. As the paper passes through these rollers, the loose toner powder melts, fusing with the fibers in the paper. The fuser rolls the paper to the output tray, and you have your finished page. The fuser wiper is a component of the fuser which looks like a windscreen/windshield wiper.
Fuser oil is used on the surface of the fuser roller in a photocopier to ensure that the toner does not stick to the paper and cause a paper jam.

Laser printers and copiers not only need toner (ink powder) for printing, but also a drum (comparable with the print head of an inkjet printer). The drum puts the toner in the right place, and afterwards the paper is heated so the toner melts and is attached permanently to the paper. Drums, like all components of a printer, wear and will have to be replaced at some time, although they are fairly durable.
Component in laser printers linking the toner to the drum.
Ink cartridges for inkjet printers.
Component in laser printers which is coated in toner particles which stick to the drum.
Materials used for cleaning printers.
Some printers use ink sticks instead of cartridges. Be careful to pick the right product for your printer.

Disk-shaped mechanism in a printing device that carries the template of the characters to be printed around its rim and prints one character at a time, revolving after each character to the proper position for the next.
null
Machine with a keyboard and a ribbon to print onto paper.
Materials used for cleaning.
Kit containing chemicals, cloths etc. used to clean equipment.

Using a laminator you can attach a clear, protective cover to your prints to make them more durable. Give the outside of reports a lasting professional look or make durable signs for use in public places!

column4: accesorios de almacenaje para máquinas de oficina
column5: Storage solutions such as ink system storage kit.
Place where information is put e.g. noticeboard, whiteboard in a classroom.
Three-sided shapes.
Supplies used in drawing such as pencils, paints and paintbrushes.
Boxes to hold cash and tickets. Usually made of metal and with a lock for security.
Plastic trays which are placed in cash boxes so notes and coins of different values can be held separately.
Technical drawing instrument used by mathematicians and craftspeople in for drawing or inscribing a circle or arc.
column6: Technical drawing instrument used by mathematicians and craftspeople in for drawing or inscribing a circle or arc.

column5: Paper used for technical drawing by draughtspeople, designers and architects.
Thin sheet of material with letters or shapes cut from it. It is placed on top of another material and then ink or paint and applied to so the letters or shapes are produced on the material below.
Film with a textured 'matte' surface on one or both sides allowing pens and pencils to be used to make designs. Erasers can be used and will not damage the film. Used by draughtspeople and designers.
Objects to place at the end of a row of books on a bookshelf to prevent the books from falling over or off the shelf.
Plastic object used to sort and store documents on your desk.
Plastic trays which are placed in desk drawers to allow you to organize things into different compartments.
Items needed for your desk such as lamps and  in-trays, as well as stationery such as notepaper and pens.
Hard covers used to protect books, printed reports etc.
Plastic items with a metal edge used to contain tape and cut it to the required length.
Item used to manually take staples out of documents
Device for fastening together sheets of paper together with a staple or staples.
Instrument used for opening envelopes by hand e.g. a sharp knife-like instrument.

Instrument used for cutting cloth, paper, and other material, consisting of two blades laid one on top of the other and fastened in the middle so as to allow them to be opened and closed by a thumb and finger inserted through rings on the end of their handles.
Cardboard or plastic tubes used for posting posters or other large rollable documents.
Envelopes with plastic wndows in the front so the address written on the letter is visible from the outside and so you do not need to write/print the address on the envelope.
Flat paper container with a sealable flap, used to enclose a letter or document.
Stationery such as notepaper and pens.
Books for storing postal/e-mail addresses as well as other important information about your contacts.
System to plan a process, operation etc.
Agendas showing the days, weeks and months of the year where you can add appointments and other important dates.
Book, usually a type of calendar or diary, in which appointments can be written.
Supplies used for mailing such as envelopes and Jiffy bags.
Big board, usually a white board placed on a wall, where week/month/yearly plans can be written, erased and re-written.
Board where detachable letters can be placed to make words or phrases.
Magnetic board where pieces of paper etc can be attached using magnets.
Board, often a pin board placed on a wall, to which bulletins, reports and other notes and posters are attached.
Folders with metal rings to keep papers and documents in order and prevent them from falling out.
Folders, binders and indexes are all made from strong paper, card or plastic and are used to store information or documents.
Plastic trays used to store index cards.
Replacement ink for ink cartridges etc.
Pads of ink, used with data stamps etc.
Additional 'leads' for reusable pencils.
Pens or rollers which contain correction fluid. Correction fluid is used to cover up mistakes on a document. The fluid dries quickly and you can write over it.
Fluid used to cover up mistakes on a document. The fluid dries quickly and you can write over it.
A felt pen is a type of marker pen with its own ink source. It's called a felt pen because of the porous felt tip from where the ink is applied on the surface.
column6: A felt pen is a type of marker pen with its own ink source. It's called a felt pen because of the porous felt tip from where the ink is applied on the surface.

column5: White or coloured material used to make markings on blackboard, concrete floors etc. Can be easily removed.
Ink pens used to make temporary or permanent markings (words, symbols, drawings) e.g non-permanent markers used on white boards.
Pencils in diferent colours e.g red, blue, green.
Pencils made out of wood.
Ball point pens use oil-based ink, which dries up almost immediately after applying on paper. The ink is evenly dispensed through a metal ball.
column6: Ball point pens use oil-based ink, which dries up almost immediately after applying on paper. The ink is evenly dispensed through a metal ball.

column5: Pens with a metal nib and a removal ink cartridge.
Sets containing pen(s) and pencil(s).
Rollerball pens use a ball point and a water-based instead of an oil-based ink. The ink in a roller ball tends to go more deeply and more widely into the paper than the ink in a ball-point pen.
column6: Rollerball pens use a ball point and a water-based instead of an oil based ink. The ink in a roller ball tends to go more deeply and more widely into the paper than the ink in a ball-point pen.

column5: Instruments used to write such as pens, pencils and market pens.
Device used for opening envelopes through a mechanical process.
Used to make something moist, for example for fingertips to help you turn pages in a book or sort through papers.
Pad placed on a desk to make it easier to write or to protect the desk from scratches.
Cover or shield for a finger.
Device for sharpening a pencil by rotating it against a cutting edge.
Device used for holding documents together e.g. a bulldog clip which is typically made of metal and is silver and black.
Piece of bent wire or plastic used for holding several sheets of paper together.
Piece of thin wire with two short right-angled end pieces which are driven by a stapler through sheets of paper to fasten them together.
Small sharp metal object used for atatching paper onto noticeboards, walls etc.
Also known as elastic bands, used for keeping items together, such a pile of letters or documents.
Device used to hold two things together e.g the small metal fastener at the back of a necklace.
Projecting pointed part on various devices e.g. forks
Small board with a spring clip at the top, used for holding papers and providing support for writing.
Folding cover or holder, typically made of stiff paper or card, for storing loose papers.
Covers, usually made of paper or card, used on the top of reports to protect them and sometimes to make them more visually appealing.
Indexes with tabs to divide the sections. Often done alphabeticaly.
Any materials used for presentation such as pens, flipcharts and paper.
Sheet of card or paper used to divide a folder or ring binder into sections.
Files to store business cards.

Opto-mechanical device for displaying motion picture film by projecting it onto a screen. Most of the optical and mechanical elements, except for the illumination and sound devices, are present in movie cameras.

Type of slide projector that is used to display images to an audience. An overhead projector typically consists of a large box containing a very bright lamp and a fan to cool it. On top of the box is a large fresnel lens that collimates the light. Above the box, typically on a long arm, is a mirror and lens that focusses and redirects the light forward instead of up.

Installation consisting of a surface and a support structure used for displaying a projected image for the view of an audience.
Lamp which enables a projector (beamer) to project/show images.

With a digital camera all the pictures you make are stored digitally, which means you can instantly view a picture after you have taken it and take as many pictures as you like, without having to buy new films all the time. It is easy to download the pictures from your camera to your computer, either at home or at the shop and edit them before printing. Once they are on your computer, you can easily share your pics with the rest of the world by putting them on-line, or e-mailing them to friends.
Cameras which store devices on a replacable film such as 35mm film.

A camera is a device used to capture images, as still photographs or as sequences of moving images (movies or videos). The term as well as the modern-day camera evolved from the camera obscura, Latin for "dark chamber", an early mechanism for projecting images, in which an entire room functioned as a real-time imaging system. Cameras may work with the light of the visible spectrum or with other portions of the electromagnetic spectrum. A camera generally consists of some kind of enclosed hollow, with an opening or aperture at one end for light to enter, and a recording or viewing surface for capturing the light at the other end. Most cameras have a lens positioned in front of the camera's opening to gather the incoming light and to focus the image, or part of the image, on the recording surface. The diameter of the aperture is often controlled by a diaphragm mechanism, but some cameras have a fixed-size aperture.

A webcam is a digital video camera that has to be connected directly to a computer or network and cannot be used seperately. Webcams are perfect for video calling and chatting: finally you can see your faraway friends or family while talking/chatting! Network attached webcams can be used as affordable security cameras.

Hand-held camcorders allow you to record your own video and make photoshots. You can always have such cameras with you to record the important moments of your life and share them with friends or family. You can even make your own movie!

You will most likely need the ordinary version, unless you want to connect two devices directly to each other, and even then most modern Ethernet network devices will automatically detect the type of cable you are using and adapt their settings to it, so they will work with both types.

That is, if you have configured your firewall correctly. This can be especially important for businesses and people with sensitive information on their computer systems. A very neat function most hardware firewalls have is the ability to securely connect the local area network to other local area networks in different locations over the Internet, thus creating a Virtual Private Network (VPN). With VPN you can safely share network resources with remote offices or play games with your friends as if you were on the same LAN!
A gateway is a router or a proxy server that routes between networks. A controller is a chip, an expansion card, or a stand-alone device that interfaces with a peripheral device.

A network switch is a computer networking device that links network segments or network devices. The term commonly refers to a multi-port network bridge that processes and routes data at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model. Switches that additionally process data at the network layer (layer 3) and above are often called layer-3 switches or multilayer switches. A network switch is made up of network switch components.

For quite some time the performance of a processor has been determined by the number of MHz the clock speed was, but nowadays clock speed doesn't have so much to do with the speed of the processor anymore. One of the best ways to compare different kinds of processors, is to look up benchmarks on the internet. LED lamps have a lifespan and electrical efficiency that is several times better than incandescent lamps, and significantly better than most fluorescent lamps, with some chips able to emit more than 100 lumens per watt.

Display of many colours, either physically on a piece of paper or on a digital format. Used for colour comparisons and measurements such as checking the colour reproduction of an imaging system, and calibration and/or profiling of digital input devices such as digital cameras, and scanners and output display systems like printers, monitors and projectors.
Machine used for making candy floss (cotton candy).
Machine used to make ice cubes.
Small plastic, wooden or metal containers for pepper or salt, with small blades used for grinding the peppercorns or salt flakes so they can be added to food.
Also known as a popcorn maker, this is a machine used for popping popcorn.
Objects into which baby feeding bottles are placed and then sterilized using steam.

Video telephone and other devices used for setting up and delivering video conferencing, which is where two or more separate locations communicate by simultaneous two-way video and audio transmissions.

An Internet Protocol (IP) phone, also known as a VoIP phone (Voice over IP) uses technologies for placing and transmitting telephone calls over an IP network, such as the Internet, instead of the traditional public switched telephone network (PSTN).
Device used to dry nails following the application of nail varnish or lacquer.
Components used in laser printers and photocopiers to
Accessories for tripods, which are three-legged camera stands, such as spare legs and stand components.
Movies or films which are stored on Blu-Ray (BD) or DVD.
Instrument that converts user information into signals or reconverts received signals.
Devices which split a single cable into more than one cable, or combines several cables into one cable.
A switch box that routes an input signal to an output line e.g. to connect several computers to a single printer.
Terminal box for electric wiring or fittings at which the wires terminate for connection to electric fixtures or appliances.
An electrical connection is where objects join to make a circuit e.g. plug from a device which connects to the mains electricity plug socket.

A coaxial RF connector is an electrical connector designed to work at radio frequencies in the multi-megahertz range. RF connectors are typically used with coaxial cables and are designed to maintain the shielding that the coaxial design offers.
Analog circuits which perform signal processing functions, specifically to remove unwanted frequency components from the signal, to enhance wanted ones, or both.

Number locks ('num locks') are keys on a computer keyboard. When they are switched on, some keys can be used to produce numbers. When switched off, these same keys have different functions e.g. they work as arrow keys for the cursor.

Antistatic device worn on the wrist  used to safely ground a person working on very sensitive electronic equipment, to prevent the buildup of static electricity on their body, which can result in electrostatic discharge (ESD).
Sprays and other chemicals used to prevent the build up of dust on surfaces.
Caps used to protect electronic conenctors to prevent them from getting damaged.

An adapter is a physical device that allows one hardware or electronic interface to be adapted (accommodated without loss of function) to another hardware or electronic interface. A remote management adapter allows you to manage systems remotely.

Computer programs used to track and store electronic documents. It is usually also capable of keeping track of the different versions modified by different users (history tracking). The term has some overlap with the concepts of content management systems. It is often viewed as a component of enterprise content management (ECM) systems and related to digital asset management, document imaging, workflow systems and records management systems.
Devices used in home and office to measure temperature and other weather conditions.

column4: equipo para redes de entrega de contenido
column5: Content delivery networks use multiple servers in many geographic locations that improve deliveries of static and streaming content. Global content requests automatically get routed to the closest servers, speeding up page loads, maximizing bandwidth and providing identical content regardless of Internet- or site-traffic spikes. Depending on traffic and number of nodes, the network's algorithms select the best routing options to deliver optimum performance and avoid bottlenecks. Equipment to create content delivery networks include servers and storage systems.

column4: accesorios para lector de código de barras
column5: Accessories for portable bar code readers.
Machine using a toothed metal cutting disc or blade. Mostly used to cut wood.
Watches designed for sports purposes. Usually include a stopwatch and other measuring devices. Often tough and waterproof or water resistant.
A console is a device used to monitor and control a network. A console extender is a devices which allow remote access to this console.
Electronic device used to check the electrical connections in a network cable.
Network device used by telecom carriers to switch high-speed optical signals e.g.OC-3, OC-12, OC-48.
Device with multiple or multi-purpose connections,used for telecommunications equipment.

Small portable telescope with added optics to present an erect image, optimized for the observation of terrestrial objects. They are used for birdwatching and other naturalist activities, for hunting, verifying a marksman's shots, surveillance, and for any other application that requires more magnification than a pair of binoculars, typically on the order of 20× to 60×.
Services which fix and repair manufacturing equipment.
Liquid cooling is a highly effective method of removing excess heat from computers which is generated by the electronic components.
Cable which carries and emits bright neon light. Mostly used for decorative and advertising purposes.
Contract signed with a mobile data provider for a certain amount of data for a mobile device (smartphone, tablet) in a given period of time (usually monthly) for a fixed charge.
Devices used to play records (vinyls) of music or speech recordings.

A VoIP phone uses Voice over IP (Voice over Internet Protocol) technologies for placing and transmitting telephone calls over an IP network, such as the Internet, instead of the traditional public switched telephone network (PSTN). An adapter connects VoIP telephones to other devices.
Clothes worn by women.
Briefs, boxers, vests and socks for men.
Trousers (pants) and shorts worn by girls.
Clothes worn by men.
Cables which move data to and from computer storage devices such as hard drives using an SAS protocol.
Clothes such as jeans and sweaters, and accessories such as hats and belts.
Protective casing for cables, usually made of plastic or rubber.
Electronic device used to display e-books.
Devices used with game consoles such as controllers and joysticks.
Accessories for hardware cooling devices, such as fans, which are used to reduce the heat produced by electronic components.
Plastic covers used to protect smartphone and tablet screens from scratching etc.

InfiniBand is a switched fabric communications link primarily used in high-performance computing. Its features include quality of service and failover, and it is designed to be scalable. Its architecture specification defines a connection between processor nodes and high performance I/O nodes such as storage devices.

A nut driver is a tool for tightening nuts and bolts, which is similar in appearance and use to a screwdriver. A nut driver bit is detachable 'socket' of various sizes which attaches to the shaft and cylindrical handle of the nut driver.
Tool used to remove the protective casing from electrical wire so connections can be made.

A punch is a hard metal rod with a shaped tip at one end and a blunt butt end at the other, which is usually struck by a hammer.A nail set is a nail punch which is used to drive the head of a nail level to or into a surface.
Power tools used to smooth surfaces by abrasion with sandpaper.
Also known as a side grinder or disc grinder, this is a handheld power tool used for cutting, grinding and polishing.
Device which produces high volumes of data discs e.g. DVDs, CDs.
Power tool used for turning screws.
Fees (money) paid to service providers for maintenance and support of hardware, software etc.

column4: servicios de facilitación en el transporte
column5: Services for the transport of goods and services.

column4: cuidado del cabello y accesorios de maquillaje
column5: Accessories used for hair care and makeup such as brushes.
These are blank Blu-Ray Discs (BDs) onto which you can store data e.g. films.
Devices which play Blu-Ray Discs. Used in home entertainment and home cinema systems to play films.
Temporary structure on the outside of a building, made of wooden planks and metal poles, used by workmen while building, repairing, or cleaning the building.

column4: opciones de suscripción de datos para móviles
column5: Options available for mobile data subscriptions e.g. how many megabytes (MB) or gigabytes (GB) per month, what type of mobile device (smartphone, tablet) you can have with the subscription.

A LED-TV is a flat panel display that uses LED backlighting instead of the cold cathode fluorescent (CCFL) backlighting used in most other LCDs. Three forms of LED may be used:

- White edge-LEDs around the rim of the screen, using a special diffusion panel to spread the light evenly behind the screen (the most usual form)

- An array of LEDs arranged behind the screen whose brightness are not controlled individually.

- A dynamic “local dimming” array of LEDs to achieve a modulated backlight light pattern
IT products that are suitable for recycling.
Device which copies digital media e.g. a DVD writer, which copies ('burns') DVDs
Organization and implementation of a complex operation.
Places where large amounts of data can be stored e.g. cloud storage.
Services which rent equipment, space, and bandwidth to business customers.
Large-scale printers used for producing newspapers, posters and other high-volume documents.

An input device is any peripheral (piece of computer hardware equipment) used to provide data and control signals to an information processing system such as a computer or other information appliance. Examples of input devices include keyboards, mouse, scanners, digital cameras and joysticks. Input device accessories include the components for input devices.
Electrically-operated switch.
Equipment that can be used to identify someone biometrically e.g. iris scans.
Device which connects to a printer or photocopier which allows documents to be put into separate bins.

A patch panel is a number of circuits, usually of the same or similar type, which appear on jacks for monitoring, interconnecting, and testing circuits in a convenient, flexible manner. Accessories for patch panels include sockets and switches.
Container for electrical connections.
Premise Branch Exchanges make connections across the internal phones of one premise e.g. office .
Containers of various shapes and sizes, usually made of plastic, to keep food fresh and free from contamination.
Device for rubbing and kneading muscles and joints of the body to relieve tension or pain.
Books, computer programs etc. which can be used for educational purposes.
Caps or covers for camera lens.
Aso known as a solid state disk or electronic disk, this is a data storage device for a computer using integrated circuit assemblies as memory to store data persistently.
Digitial thermometers which are used to measure the temperature of someone's body.
Also known as CCTV, these are video cameras used inside and outside to monitor people for security reasons.

column4: accesorios para carcasas de cámaras a prueba de agua
column5: Accessories for underwater camera housing, which is protective covering/shell and stands/supports for cameras which are used underwater.
Device that makes a loud prolonged signal or warning sound e.g. ambulance siren.

Device that detects moving objects, particularly people. A motion detector is often integrated as a component of a system that automatically performs a task or alerts a user of motion in an area e.g. intruder or burglar alarm.
Protective covering/shell and stands/supports for cameras which are used outside e.g. security cameras.

column4: carcasas de cámaras a prueba de agua
column5: Protective covering/shell and stands/supports for cameras which are used underwater.
Also known as a USB stick or a USB pen, these are small devices with a USB connector which can be connected to a computer or other electronic device and used to store data.
Object which supports a CPU (Central Processing Unit in a computer) and holds it in place.

column4: soportes para proyector y soportes de pared
column5: Object which is placed on the floor or attached to the ceiling or wall, used to hold a projector in place.
Small clock worn  on a strap on one’s wrist. Can be analog, digital or new-generation smartwatch.

Device  that provides access to the system console of a computing device via networking technologies. Most commonly, a console server provides a number of serial ports, which are then connected to the serial ports of other equipment, such as servers, routers or switches. The consoles of the connected devices can then be accessed by connecting to the console server over a serial link such as a modem, or over a network with terminal emulator software such as telnet or ssh, maintaining survivable connectivity that allows remote users to log in the various consoles without being physically nearby.
Accessories for water pumps such as pipes and hose connectors.

column4: accesorios para montajes en pared y techo
column5: Accessories for wall and ceiling mounts such as screws, nuts and brackets.

column4: soportes de techo para pantalla plana
column5: Bracket or support used to hang a flat panel from the ceiling.

column4: módulos digitales y analógicos I / O
column5: I/O refers to Input/Output, which is the transfer of data between the CPU and a peripheral device. I/O modules, which can be digital and analog, are self-contained components that interact between the CPU and peripherals.
Radio frequency (RF) modems transmit radio waves wirelessly over a certain range, which can be tens of kilometres.
Also known as a terminal server, this is a device that enables you to connect devices with an RS-232, RS-422 or RS-485 serial interface to a local area network (LAN).
Small components used in serial communication interfaces such as serial ports.
Low-melting alloy, especially one based on lead and tin or (for higher temperatures) on brass or silver, used for joining less fusible metals with a soldering iron.
Small beauty tools, shaped like tongs, applied to the eyelashs to give them curl.
Devices which work on cellular (mobile) networks.

A network switch is a computer networking device that is used to connect many devices together on a computer network. A network switch module is a self-contained hardware or software component that interfaces between a network switch and other devices.
Memory (RAM) built into the printer, which is used to store and process print jobs sent from the computer.

Also known as a fog machine or fog generator, this is a device that emits a dense vapor that appears similar to fog or smoke. This artificial fog is most commonly used in professional entertainment applications e.g. in nightclubs and discos.

Also known as a multitester and a VOM (Volt-Ohm meter), this is an electronic measuring instrument that combines several measurement functions in one unit. A typical multimeter would include basic features such as the ability to measure voltage, current, and resistance.
Small electric household appliance used to vacuum dirt and dust from floors and carpets. Has a long handle, looks like a lightweight upright hoover.
Appliances for crushing ice so that it can be put into drinks or used for freezing food.
Device similar to an electric kettle, used for making tea.
Machine used to produce bubbles for children's entertainment.

Also known as a mirror ball or glitter ball, this is a roughly spherical object that reflects light directed at it in many directions, producing a complex display. Its surface consists of hundreds or thousands of facets, nearly all of approximately the same shape and size, and each having a mirrored surface. Usually it is mounted well above the heads of the people present, suspended from a device that causes it to rotate steadily on a vertical axis, and illuminated by spotlights, so that stationary viewers experience beams of light flashing over them, and see myriad spots of light spinning around the walls of the room.
Instrument which measures the working speed of an engine (especially in a road vehicle), typically in revolutions per minute.
Device which converts video signals/data into other types of signals/data, or vice versa.
Device which can create a vacuum seal in a plastic bag in order to keep the contents of the bag fresh.
Accessories for vacuum sealers such as bags and containers.

Also known as a cash till, this is a mechanical or electronic device for calculating and recording sales transactions, and an attached drawer (storage space) for storing cash. The cash register also usually prints a receipt for the customer.

This is a component of a printer. With spooling, multiple processes can write documents to a print queue without waiting. As soon as a process has written its document to the spool device, the process can perform other tasks, while a separate printing process operates the printer.
Device for sharpening knives to make them cut more effectively.

A Network interface is a systems interface (software and/or hardware) between two pieces of equipment or protocol layers in a network. A network interface processor is a device which allows the network interface to operate.
Fruit juice from which the water has been removed. Commonly consumed at home.
Plastic cards with nothing printed on them. Used in plastic card printers to produce bespoke cards.
Power tool which can be used for various cutting tasks with various materials.

Plastic gun which uses a continuous heating element to melt plastic glue, which may be pushed through the gun by a mechanical trigger mechanism, or directly by the user. The glue squeezed out of the heated nozzle is initially hot enough to burn and blister skin. The glue is tacky when hot, and solidifies in a few seconds to one minute.

Stringed musical instrument, with a fretted fingerboard, typically incurved sides, and six or twelve strings, played by plucking or strumming with the fingers or a plectrum. Can be acoustic or electric.
Object or device for producing musical sounds e.g guitar, violin.
Also known as rubbish bins or trash cans, this is a container for waste.

Percussion instrument sounded by being struck with sticks or the hands, typically cylindrical, barrel-shaped, or bowl-shaped, with a taut membrane over one or both ends. Often played with other drums in a collection known as a drum kit.
Cleaning device that uses ultrasound (usually from 20–400 kHz) and an appropriate cleaning solvent (sometimes ordinary tap water) to clean delicate items e.g. jewellery, electronics.
Kitchen utensil with a broad, flat blade for lifting foods such as cake and fish.
Coffee beans, ground coffee or coffee powder. Used to make coffee.
Cleaning appliances or devices that use steam to quickly dry, clean, and sanitize surfaces. Often the process is effective enough to disinfect or even sterilize the surfaces.
Devices used for heating water in homes and other buildings for hot water and heating systems.
Instrument used to locate fish underwater by detecting reflected pulses of sound energy (sonar).
Devices used in the home such as washing machines and fridges.
Accessories for telescopes such as stands, tripods and cases.
Allows you to adjust the temperature in an indoor space by heating or cooling the air.
Sewing means to join, fasten, or repair (something) by making stitches with a needle and thread or a sewing machine. sIroning means to smooth clothes, sheets, etc. with an iron.
These are objects and pieces of furniture found in the bathroom such as toilet bowls.
Tools used for gardening e.g. cutting and trimming plants and hedges, planting flower bulbs.
Machine that uses a revolving blade or blades to cut a lawn (grass) at an even height.

Tool which uses a flexible monofilament line instead of a blade for cutting grass and other plants near objects. It consists of a cutting head at the end of a long shaft with a handle or handles and sometimes a shoulder strap.

This is a mechanical or electronic timepiece used to assist in tracking the hours worked by an employee of a company. In the mechanical version, heavy paper card called a timesheet is inserted into a slot on the time clock. When the time card hits a contact at the rear of the slot, the machine prints day and time information on the card.

A tachograph is a device fitted to a vehicle that automatically records its speed and distance, together with the driver's activity selected from a choice of modes. For modern tachographs,the data is recorded digitally on a tachograph card, which is a digital card containing a microchip with flash memory. A tachograph card reader is a device that can read a tachograph card.

A smart card is a pocket-sized plastic card with embedded integrated circuits. Smart cards can provide identification, authentication, data storage and application processing. Smart card software is a computer program used to control and manage smart cards.

A smart card is a pocket-sized plastic card with embedded integrated circuits. Smart cards can provide identification, authentication, data storage and application processing. Smart card readers are devices which can read smart cards.
Object for a child to play with, typically a model or miniature replica of something.

RAID is a storage technology that combines multiple disk drive components into a logical unit for the purposes of data redundancy and performance improvement. Data is distributed across the drives in one of several ways, referred to as RAID levels, depending on the specific level of redundancy and performance required. A RIAD controller, which is a type of disk array controller, is a device which manages the physical disk drives and presents them to the computer as logical units.
Fine net hung across a door or window or around a bed to keep mosquitoes away.
Devices which control the speed of a fan.
Device to pump water from one place to another, used to drain flood water, clean ponds and pools or stop building foundations from becoming submerged.
Devices which allow e-mails to be stored and archived separately so that they free up space on the hard disk and so that they are stored safely.

Also known as phototherapy, light therapy consists of exposure to daylight or to specific wavelengths of light using polychromatic polarised light, lasers, light-emitting diodes, fluorescent lamps, dichroic lamps or very bright, full-spectrum light, usually controlled with various devices. The light is administered for a prescribed amount of time and, in some cases, at a specific time of day. It can be used in the treatment of skin disorders, sleep disorder and some psychiatric disorders.
Depilation - removal of body or facial hair from its root - using light.

column4: productos para el cuidado de la piel
column5: Creams and other products applied to skin to keep it clean and healthy.

column4: platos y utensilios para niños pequeños
column5: Gving food to toddler, which is a child between 1-3 years old.
Contains presents/gifts for babies such as soft toys.
Appliance that increases humidity (moisture) in a single room or in an entire building. Commonly used in artificially heated spaces.

Also known as a  hammer drill, roto-drill or hammering drill, a hammer drill is a rotary drill with a hammering action. The hammering action provides a short, rapid hammer thrust to destroy relatively brittle material and allow quicker drilling with less effort. These tools are usually electrically powered, and increasingly powered by batteries.
Tool used for cutting arbitrary curves, such as stenciled designs or other custom shapes, into a piece of wood, metal, or other material.
Small binoculars used to see things from a long distance e.g. for watching the opera in a theatre.
Lenses, plates and other accessories for microscopes.
Optical instrument used for viewing very small objects, such as mineral samples or animal or plant cells, typically magnified several hundred times.
These are lights used in discos, clubs and other venues for flashing, different colours and other effects.

Printer emulation allows printers to emulate other printers. For example, if a non-HP printer emulates an HP printer, any software written for a real HP printer will also run in the non-HP printer emulation and produce equivalent printing. Printer emulation upgrades means updating the software so that it is the latest version.

column4: dispositivos para optimización y monitoreo de redes
column5: Devices which check how the network is running and ensure that it is running at its most efficient (optimum).

Also known as a security token, this is a device used to prove one's identity electronically e.g. when accessing a bank account. The authenticator is used in addition to or in place of a password to prove that the user is who they claim to be.
Computer program that allows you to manage a service such as online retail.

Optical instrument designed to make distant objects appear nearer. It contains an arrangement of lenses, or of curved mirrors and lenses, by which rays of light are collected and focused and the resulting image magnified.
Chemical used to remove limescale from kettles, taps, baths etc.
An audio CD (compact disc) is used to record and store audio content such as music or speech. Played back using a CD player or CD drive in a computer etc.

Radio that can both transmit and receive. A two-way radio allows the operator to have a conversation with other similar radios operating on the same radio frequency (channel). Two-way radios are available in mobile, stationary base and hand-held portable configurations. Hand-held radios are often called walkie-talkies.
Device that measures distance from the observer to a target. Commonly used in photography and engineering.
Mixers and food processors are used to chop, mix and puree food. They have various attachments such as blades and mills.
Small piece of plastic used to cover the lens of a camera to protect it from scratches and dirt.
Printers which print on blank plastic cards to produce bespoke designs.
Device that allows power to be controlled remotely.

Also known as a mixing console, sound board, mixing desk, and audio production console, an audio mixer is an electronic device for combining ("mixing"), routing, and changing the level, timbre and/or dynamics of audio signals. A mixer can mix analog or digital signals, depending on the type of mixer. The modified signals (voltages or digital samples) are summed to produce the combined output signals.
Appliances to make yogurt at home.
Device with multiple ports which allows separate computers to display their video outputs on a single screen.
Appliances to make chocolate at home.

Electrical kitchen device used for slicing foods. An electric knife requires less physical effort than an ordinary knife and produces neater slices. The device consists of two serrated blades that are clipped together. When the appliance is switched on the blades continuously move lengthways to provide the sawing action.

A personal FM transmitter is a low-power FM radio transmitter which purpose is to allow music or other audio content from a portable media player, CD player or other portable audio system to be played through a nearby FM radio.

A doorbell is an electronic signaling device typically placed near an entry door to a building. When a visitor presses a button the bell rings inside the building, alerting the occupant to the presence of the visitor.
Components such as timers and thermostats which control cooking devices.
Heat-resistant piece of material, normally with an elasticated edge, used to cover an ironing board.
Cooking appliance used in the home to grill/fry hot dogs (sausages).
Device for serving chocolate fondue (melted chocolate).
Also known as a gift token, this is a piece of paper which can be given to a shop, cinemas etc. in place of money. Often given as gifts for birthdays and special occasions.
Fixed basin with a water supply (taps/faucets)and a drain, found in bathrooms, kitchens etc.
Sprays and powders used to repel and kill insects.

Also known as a tap, this is device by which a flow of liquid or gas from a pipe or container can be controlled. Water faucets are found in kitchens and bathrooms. There can be separate cold and hot faucets or one that produces both cold and hot water.
Electrical device allowing two-way communication between someone inside a building and someone at the front door.
Device that automatically regulates temperature, or that activates a device when the temperature reaches a certain point.
Airtight pot in which food can be cooked quickly under steam pressure.
POS (Point of Sale) or mobile printers are used to print receipts and other documents in retail.
Services which manage the purchasing and delivery of products from suppliers (wholesalers) to physical and online retails.

column4: accesorios para artículos de cocina y hogar
column5: Accessories for the kitchen and house such as containers and cloths.

Sometimes referred to by the merchandising term personal video recorder (PVR),this is a consumer electronics device or application software that records video in a digital format to a disk drive, USB flash drive, SD memory card, SSD or other local or networked mass storage device. The term includes set-top boxes (STB) with direct to disk recording facility, portable media players (PMP) with recording, recorders (PMR) as camcorders that record onto Secure Digital memory cards and software for personal computers which enables video capture and playback to and from a hard disk drive.

Structure including metallic rod placed on top of buildings. If lightning strikes it will preferentially strike the rod and be conducted to ground through the wire, instead of passing through the structure, where it could start a fire or cause electrocution.
Devices that allow you to speak on the phone hands-free by using a speaker and  a microphone.
null
Place for a domestic fire, especially a grate or hearth at the base of a chimney.

Filters used on cameras to modify the images recorded e.g. to change the colours or to make black-white images. The filter can be a square or oblong shape mounted in a holder accessory, or, more commonly, a glass or plastic disk with a metal or plastic ring frame, which can be screwed in front of or clipped onto the lens.
Speaker which produces bass sounds (low-pitched audio frequencies).
Also known as dummies, these are plastic devices placed in babies' mouths to stop them crying and keep them happy.
A toy for babies who are teething (growing teeth).
Also known as a water cooler, this is piece of office equipment used for dispensing cold or cool water. The water can come from the mains or from a bottle which is attached to the dispenser.

Mechanical device that extracts milk from the breasts of a lactating woman. Breast pumps may be manual devices powered by hand or foot movements or electrical devices powered by electricity or batteries.
Device used to measure the amount of light. Commonly used by photographers.
Accessory for notebook computers that helps reduce their operating temperature.They are intended to protect both the notebook from overheating and the user from suffering heat-related discomfort.

A type of soft lighting device used in photography. A "soft box" is an enclosure around a bulb comprising reflective side and back walls and a diffusing material at the front of the light. The sides and back of the box are lined with a bright surface - an aluminized fabric surface or an aluminum foil -  to act as an efficient reflector.
Electric device used to straighten hair. Also known as a hair iron or a hair tong.
Fridges and freezers that stand next to each other in the kitchen.
Suitcases, backpacks and other bags for carrying luggage.
Bases for telephones.
Recycling of glass, plastic, paper and other materials. Some larger electrical objects and white goods can also be (part) recycled.
Object, sometimes wedged, placed next to or under a door to prevent it from closing.
Device consisting of a circular canopy of cloth on a folding metal frame supported by a central rod, used as protection against rain.
Cameras that take pcitures and print them a short time later.
Cream or substance applied to the face to give the skin a brown tinge (fake tan).
Flat cable with a PATA interface, used to connect storage devices such as hard disks, floppy drives, and optical disc drives in computers.
A nailer is a device for putting nails into wood. A pneumatic nailer is the most common type of power nail guns. They are powered by air pressure from a small compressor, and are quick ansd powerful.
Devices which distribute audio and video signals over long distances.
Components of a computer case.
Tool for shaping wood. They are used to flatten, reduce the thickness of, and impart a smooth surface to a rough piece of lumber or timber.
Fridges that also have freezer departments, usually at the top.
A drive bay is a standard area for adding hardware to a computer. Most drive bays are fixed to the inside of a case, but some can be removed.
Portable electric jigsaw, powered by a battery or battery pack and can operate without a power cord or cable attached to a fixed electricity supply.
DVD/Blu-Ray players that can are lightweight and portable. Some have an integral screen, others need to be attached to an external monitor.

Also called "combi drills," these are very powerful tools which move the drill bit in and out while it is spinning. Used in demolition work. Powered by a battery or battery pack and can operate without a power cord or cable attached to a fixed electricity supply.
Power saw with a rapidly rotating toothed disc. Powered by a battery or battery pack and can operate without a power cord or cable attached to a fixed electricity supply.

Tool with a rotating abrasive disc, used to grind, polish, or cut metal and other materials. Powered by a battery or battery pack and can operate without a power cord or cable attached to a fixed electricity supply.

Tool used in gardening, carpenty and construction for cutting various materials. Powered by a battery or battery pack and can operate without a power cord or cable attached to a fixed electricity supply.
Tool which fastens or fixes things in place with tacks. Powered by a battery or battery pack and can operate without a power cord or cable attached to a fixed electricity supply.
These are places where steam irons are placed to produce the steam.
Small handheld beauty device which uses a heated element to curl hair.

Tool with a flattened or cross-shaped tip that fits into the head of a screw to turn it, which is powered by a battery or battery pack and can operate without a power cord or cable attached to a fixed electricity supply.

Tool with a rotating cutting tip or reciprocating hammer or chisel, used for making holes. Powered by a battery or battery pack and can operate without a power cord or cable attached to a fixed electricity supply.

Tool shaped like a gun which applies hot melted adhesive (glue) to a surface which dries in a short time. Powered by a battery or battery pack and can operate without a power cord or cable attached to a fixed electricity supply.
Mobile phone that is able to perform many of the functions of a computer, typically having a relatively large screen and an operating system capable of running general-purpose applications.

Electronic amplifier that amplifies low-power audio signals (signals composed primarily of frequencies between 20 - 20 000 Hz, the human range of hearing) to a level suitable for driving loudspeakers and is the final stage in a typical audio playback chain.
